{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4b010ac7-5524-4c89-adff-e779349ed7ef","content":"## Debugging a C# MCP Server with MCP Inspector\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n(Or point to a published DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourServer.dll`)\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your server as a child process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Use the tabs** to:\n- **Tools** → list & invoke your tools with sample inputs\n- **Resources / Prompts** → test those if exposed\n- View raw JSON-RPC messages in the message log\n\n**Key tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout only**. Route any logging/debug output to **stderr** — otherwise the Inspector can't parse the protocol stream.\n- If you use `Console.WriteLine` for logging, switch to `Console.Error.WriteLine` or a stderr-targeted logger.\n- You can set environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs them (e.g., API keys).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"54f4dc89-af47-473a-95ce-ed76708bc311","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to search a codebase for this. Let me provide a concise, helpful answer.","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"F41A:19DD:154E1C0:176188A:69FDA8C0"},"id":"4d7c78dc-5a47-4186-b359-681995d80cce","timestamp":"2026-05-08T09:11:45.356Z","parentId":"0da75341-c795-4f02-bffc-ed251599f7cb"}
